english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Cultivating Truth
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Hall of Cultivating Truth was the dwelling of the former Grand Protector of Andong, Master Kiang. Master Kiang had long been afflicted with illness. Through his cousin Kim Jang-won, he entreated me to write this record. I myself fell ill before Master Kiang did, and though I have since recovered, I remain weak, and at times sharp pains assail me still, leaving me unable to rise. Yet I have returned to service at court, entering the royal hall with seeming vigor for a few months before my dismissal—thus the illness revealed itself anew. Only I know the truth of this. It is fitting, then, that Master Kiang sought not the eloquent speakers of this age, but turned to me.

    When a person receives this vital breath and is born, Heaven remains firm and Earth remains yielding—this alone suffices. Breaking it down further: water, fire, wood, metal, and earth—this alone suffices. When we seek the source where yang moves in odd numbers and yin moves in even numbers, where yang transforms and yin changes, we find it returns only to the truth of the Limitless. This truth of the Limitless is difficult to capture in words. The Book of Poetry says: "The work of Heaven above has neither sound nor smell." Is this not where the Limitless dwells? Therefore, Master Chou composed the Diagram of the Great Ultimate and declared: "The Limitless is the Great Ultimate." Thus did he elucidate how the Great Ultimate and the Limitless are one.

    In Heaven, all is whole and undifferentiated—before wind stirs and thunder moves. In humanity, all is still and quiescent—before responding to affairs and encountering things. If the wholeness of Heaven can remain unchanged when wind stirs and thunder moves, then how should the stillness of humanity be maintained when responding to affairs and encountering things? Consider a mirror: beauty and ugliness belong to the reflected object, while the mirror itself bears no trace. Does the mirror ever become soiled by the very act of reflecting? Thus we know that human nature, being inherently true, is preserved only by the great person, who thereby becomes great. This greatness comes not from without. Serving one's lord with propriety is not flattery but truth. Visiting the sick and mourning the dead is not deception but truth.

    But in these times, private interest grows without end. Men scheme to tear each other down and use cunning to elevate themselves, only to find their pursuit of wholeness becomes their ruin. Such cases abound. Is not the practice of falsehood becoming ever more clumsy?

    Though Master Kiang suffers from illness, he has named his hall "Cultivating Truth," which shows plainly that he remains untempted by the world's allurements. As for me, I am but a student of hearsay and recitation. Though I do not lack understanding of how to cultivate the heart, I am unable to practice it. There is a saying from the land of Zou: "In cultivating the heart, nothing surpasses reducing desire." Let me therefore take this as the first principle of cultivating truth: to reduce desire.

    Written on the first day of the seventh month in the year Gyeongsin.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Hall of Cultivating Truth' (養眞齋) represents a philosophical ideal rooted in Neo-Confucian thought, particularly the concept of preserving one's true nature untouched by worldly corruption.
    - Master Chou (周子) refers to Zhou Dunyi, the influential Neo-Confucian philosopher who developed the Diagram of the Great Ultimate (太極圖), a foundational cosmological schema in Neo-Confucian philosophy.
    - The mirror metaphor is a classical Buddhist and Daoist image representing the mind's capacity to reflect reality without being affected by what it perceives, central to the cultivation of truth.
    - The reference to the land of Zou alludes to Mencius, who was from the state of Zhou, emphasizing the Mencian principle that reducing desires is essential to moral cultivation.
